<setup>
<selectFromSequence name="a" from="2" to="5"/>
<selectFromSequence name="b" from="6" to="9"/>
<selectFromSequence name="c" from="-3" to="3" exclude="0"/>  
<function name="f">
    $c + $b/(x-$a)
  </function>
  <derivative name="fP">$f</derivative>  
</setup>

  <p>
    Consider the function <m>f(x) = $f</m>.  We are going to use the limit definition of the derivative to determine <m>f'(x)</m>.

    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          Recall that the limit definition of <m>f'(x)</m> is
          <me> f'(x) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} </me>
          and thus we need to determine expressions for <m>f(x+h)</m> and <m>f(x+h) - f(x)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>Using the given formula, <m>f(x) = $f</m>, 
      which of the following expressions is equivalent to <m>f(x+h)</m>?</p>
            <answer>
              <choiceInput>
                <choice><m>f(x+h) = $f + h </m></choice>
                <choice credit="1"><m>f(x+h)= $c + \frac{$b}{x+h-$a} </m>  </choice>
                <choice><m>f(x+h)= <math simplify>$c - $b/$a</math> + \frac{9}{x} + \frac{9}{h} </m>  </choice>          
                <choice><m>f(x+h) = $f + \frac1h </m>  </choice>
              </choiceInput>
            </answer>  
      </li>
      <li>
      <p>First, verify that 
        <me>
          f(x+h) - f(x) = $c + \frac{$b}{x+h-$a} - \left( $f \right) = \frac{$b}{x+h-$a} - \frac{$b}{x-$a}.  
        </me>
        Then, get a common denominator to subtract the two fractions and simplify the numerator as much as possible.  Which of the following expression results?
      </p>
            <answer>
              <choiceInput>
                <choice><m>f(x+h) - f(x) = \frac{<math>$b*h</math>}{(x+h-$a)(x-$a)} </m></choice>
                <choice><m>f(x+h) - f(x) =  \frac{<math simplify>-$b*h - 2*$b*$a</math>}{(x+h-$a)(x-$a)} </m>  </choice>
                <choice credit="1"><m>f(x+h) - f(x) =  \frac{<math>-$b*h</math>}{(x+h-$a)(x-$a)} </m> </choice>  
                <choice ><m>f(x+h)  - f(x) =  \frac{-h}{(x+h-$a)^2}</m>  </choice> 
              </choiceInput>
            </answer>   
      </li>
      <li> 
        <p>
          Next, use your work from (b) to substitute the simplest possible expression for <m>f(x+h)-f(x)</m> in the space provided:
        </p>  

        <setup>
          <boolean name="exprCorrect">$dq_x1 = (-$b h)/((x + h - $a)(x-$a))</boolean>
          <matchesPattern name="singleFraction" pattern="-()/()">$dq_x1</matchesPattern>
        </setup>
        <p><m>f'(x)= \displaystyle \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} = \lim_{h \to 0} </m> <mathInput name="dq_x1" minwidth="70"></mathInput> <m>\cdot \frac{1}{h}</m>
      <!-- <answer><award><when>$dq_x1 = 
        \frac{<math>-$b*h</math>}{(x+h-$a)(x-$a)}
      </when></award></answer> -->
      <answer>
        <award>
          <when>$exprCorrect and $singleFraction</when>
        </award>
      </answer>
        </p>
        <!-- testing 
        <p><math simplify>$$f(x+h) - $$f(x)</math></p>
        <p><math simplify>-$b*h/((x+h-$a)(x-$a))</math></p>
        <p>exprCorrect = $exprCorrect</p>
        <p>singleFraction = $singleFraction</p>
       /testing -->
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Finally, evaluating the limit by letting <m>h \to 0</m>, we determine the value of <m>f'(x)</m>:</p>
        <p><m>f'(x) = </m> <answer>$$fP(x)</answer></p>
      </li>

    </ol>
  </p>